    "A New and Concise Bible Dictionary": "Rebekah's nurse: she accompanied her mistress when she left Padan-aram and remained with her till her death; she was buried under the 'oak of weeping.' Gen. 24: 59; Gen. 35: 8.\n1. Son of Raamah, son of Cush. His descendants are supposed to have located themselves on the Persian Gulf. Gen. 10: 7; 1 Chr. 1: 9.",
    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "The Holy Spirit (Gal. 3:5) which is a Divine spirit.\n1. The Holy Spirit (Gal. 3:5) which is a Divine spirit. [v_Rev_16_13]",
    "Frederick Dale Bruner": "The Three Self-Denials of Love, 17:24-18:9 A. Love Limits Its Freedom (Flexibility): The Payment of the Temple Tax, 17:24-27 B. Love Redirects Its Ambition (Humility): The Question of Greatness, 18:1-5 C. Love Doesn't Want to Hurt Anyone's Faith (Sensitivity): Skandala, 18:6-\n1. Stendahl, 788, and Beare, 276, also think this section in Matthew is against false teachers. For the important verb skandalizo, see Stahlin's article, TDNT, 7:339-58; the word's main meaning, ibid., 351, is \"`to cause loss of faith,' i.e., `to rob of eternal salvation.\"' Consequently, Luz, 3:19, believes the verb should be translated \"ensnare\" or even \"destroy,\" and not merely a tepid \"offend.\" See good examples of the word's meaning in Luther, Matt 1824, W2, 7:880-",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And there was a famine in the land, etc.] In the land of Canaan, as the Targum of Jonathan expresses it; besides the first famine that was in the days of Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`; of which (see [v_Gen_12_10] <011210>Genesis 12:10); which was an hundred years before this; and Isaac went unto Abimelech king of the Philistines, unto Gerar; where his father Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]` had sojourned before he was born; and therefore the present king of this place can scarce be thought to be the same Abimelech that was king of it in Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`\u2019s time; but it is highly probable that this Abimelech was the son of the former king, and that this was a common name to the kings of Gerar or the Philistines, as Pharaoh was to the kings of Egypt `[nation_Egypt_Ref]`. Isaac came to this place from Lahairoi, where he had dwelt many [v_Gen_24_62] years, (see <012462>Genesis 24:62 25:11); which was at or near Beersheba, and was about eight miles from Gerar f1416. 466\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "Scourged . The terrible Roman scourging carried with it into the provinces the Latin word, which is here borrowed into the Greek of Matt. and Mark, and so into the Syriac (Pesh.) and Coptic (Memph.) Jerome here remarks that it was according to the Roman laws that one who is crucified shal first be scourged. Wet. quotes Greek, Roman, and Jewish writers as showing that it was common to scourge before crucifying; compare Jos. above. The sufferer was stripped and bound to a pillar or post, bending forward so as to expose his back completely; the heavy whip or strap often contained bits of bone or metal, and tore the quivering flesh into one bloody mass. The law of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` had provided, (Deuteronomy 25:3) that a scourging should not exceed forty stripes, and Jewish custom made sure of this by stopping at \"forty save one'\"; (2 Corinthians 11:24) but the Roman scourgers were restricted by nothing but strength and inclination. We ought to feel a shuddering gratitude at our inability to conceive the consequences of this cruel infliction. Delivered , to some of his soldiers. (Matthew 27:27.) VI. Matthew 27:27-\n1. Luke gives much that they do not contain, and John `[char_John_Ref]`'s narrative is nearly al additional to the other three. Matthew's account divides itself into Matthew 27:3, Matthew 27:2- 34, Matthew 27:35-38, Matthew 27:39-44, Matthew 27:45-50, Matthew 27:51-56.\u00e2\u20ac\u201dthe time of the crucifixion was beyond question from about 9 A. M. to 8 P. M., and probably A. D. 30; if so, the day of the month was probably April 7 (Wieseler, p. 855, Clark's \"Harm.\" p. 291). As to the place, see below on Matthew 27:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "Scourged. The terrible Roman scourging carried with it into the provinces the Latin word, which is here borrowed into the Greek of Matt. and Mark, and so into the Syriac (Pesh.) and Coptic (Memph.) Jerome here remarks that it was according to the Roman laws that one who is crucified shall first be scourged. Wet. quotes Greek, Roman, and Jewish writers as showing that it was common to scourge before crucifying; compare Jos. above. The sufferer was stripped and bound to a pillar or post, bending forward so as to expose his back completely; the heavy whip or strap often contained bits of bone or metal, and tore the quivering [v_Deu_25_3] flesh into one bloody mass. The law of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` had provided, (Deuteronomy 25:3) that a scourging should not exceed forty stripes, and Jewish custom made sure of this by stopping at \"forty save [v_2Co_11_24] one'\"; (2 Corinthians 11:24) but the Roman scourgers were restricted by nothing but strength and inclination. We ought to feel a shuddering gratitude at our inability to conceive the consequences of [v_Mat_27_27] this cruel infliction. Delivered, to some of his soldiers. (Matthew 27:27.) [v_Mat_27_27] [v_Mat_27_28] [v_Mat_27_29] [v_Mat_27_30] [v_Mat_27_31] VI. Matthew 27:27-\n1. Luke gives much that they do not contain, and John `[char_John_Ref]`'s narrative is nearly [v_Mat_27_3] all additional to the other three. Matthew's account divides itself into Matthew 27:3, Matthew 27:2- [v_Mat_27_35] [v_Mat_27_36] [v_Mat_27_37] [v_Mat_27_38] 34, Matthew 27:35-38, Matthew 27:39-44, Matthew 27:45-50, Matthew 27:51-56.\u00e2\u20ac\u201dthe time of the crucifixion was beyond question from about 9 A. M. to 8 P. M., and probably A. D. 30; if so, the day of the month was probably April 7 (Wieseler, p. 855, Clark's \"Harm.\" p. 291). As to the place, see [v_Mat_27_33] below on Matthew 27:33. [v_Mat_27_32] [v_Mat_27_33] [v_Mat_27_34] I. Matthew 27:32-",
