    "Frederick Dale Bruner": "The usual and most obvious interpretation of the text is that of personal discipline in one's own life; see, for example, Schlatter, Das Evangelium, 279-80; McNeile, 262; and Grundmann, 416, who writes that passion \"proceeds from the hand that grasps after the forbidden, from the foot that hurries to the unallowed, and from the eye that looks longingly at the thing that it is against the law to long for. No sacrifice can be high enough ... , for the life and destruction of a human being in eternity is in the balances\" Davies and Allison, 2:767, are similar: \"The war with sin in the here and now determines one's final destiny,\" and they cite Plummer's remark to the effect: \"'We sacrifice even the most valuable of our limbs, in order to avoid the death of the body by incurable disease. We ought to be ready to sacrifice things of still greater value in order to avoid the death of the soul.\"' There is, they conclude, a \"life-giving mortification\" (Symeon the New Theologian). For thorough discussion of gehenna, the Greek word used here for our word \"hell,\" see Jeremias's article in TDNT,1:657-58, which concludes: \"In the NT there is no description of the torments of hell as [there is] in apocalyptic literature. If [the torments] are mentioned it is only to rouse consciences to fear the wrath of the heavenly Judge.... The severity of the judgment of God on sin is expressed by Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` in His threatening of geenna even to disciples who wound their brothers.... No sacrifice is too costly in the war against sin (M [ark] 9:43ff. [emphases added]).\" Milton's aetiology of gehenna-hell is correct, even if in poetic form (Paradise Lost, 1:392-405). II. THE THREE OTHER-CONCERNS OF LOVE, 18:10-35 A. The Love That Seeks Others Out (Visitation), 18:10-14 \"Watch out that you don't ever look down on even one of these least significant little people! For I tell you, their angels in heaven are constantly looking into the face of my Father in heaven. Tell me what you think: if a man had a hundred sheep and one of them wandered off, wouldn't he leave the ninety-nine on the hills and go seek out the one wandering away? And if he finds it, amen, I tell you, he rejoices more over it than over the ninety-nine that never got lost. Thus it is not the will of your Father in heaven that even one of these least significant little people should ever self-destruct.' 11 After Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` told us three ways to deny ourselves, he now teaches us three ways to seek out others. And the first \"others\" to whom he directs our attention are those beginning to leave the Christian fellowship. 18noa Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' introduction to this teaching is surprising: \"Watch out that you don't ever look down on even one of these least significant little people.\" Those who are least significant in the Christian community are those who are on the fence, who are half in and half out, who are half-hearted in their devotion to Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` and to the Christian enterprise. Their insignificance is due in part to their spiritual indifference. (These weak Christians almost exactly resemble the first three soils in the Parable of the Sower) 13:4-7,13-15, 18-22.) The temptation for the spiritually serious is to look down on half-hearted or \"nominal\" Christians to whom Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ seems to mean too little. Fourth-soil Christians find it hard to like the three less serious soils because they rightly despise unseriousness in themselves. But, surprisingly, Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` asks us to learn the hard art of not hating in others what we hate in ourselves. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` seeks nothing less than moral regeneration because this art is in fact humanly impossible. Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]`' admonition not to look down one's nose at even one of the least significant but to get rid of our own hurtful habits is in effect a second or even third invitation to conversion - to the conversion of serious Christians. We should note again the recurring \"one.\" Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` is not asking for a cosmic love; he is asking for an almost banal love of unattractive individuals. \"Don't look down on even one insignificant person!\" In every believing community there is at least one person for whom we feel something like deserved contempt. Such people Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` now upgrades. The identification of the insignificant mikroi, the \"little ones\" (RSV, NRSV, NEB, REB, TEV, NJB), is different in different interpreters. Chrysostom, 59:4:367-68, is correctly convinced that the little ones of whom Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` speaks are not really little ones or insignificant persons, but those considered such by others, \"for how should he be little who is equal in value to the whole world? [18:13-14]; how should he be little who is dear to God?\" In a fine characterization, McNeile, 264, believes the little ones include \"all who are `little,' whether in age [chil dren], worldly importance [the poor], or religious development [unfruitful Christians], including (as vv.12ff. imply) sinners\" See 18:iob. Cf. Thompson, 163-",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "And he went up from thence to Beersheba.] From the place he last, removed unto Beersheba; the famine being over, he returns to the [v_Gen_21_33] place where he and his rather formerly lived, (<012133>Genesis 21:33 22:19).\nVer.",
    "Commentary Vol. 90": "Henry: \"The Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` suffered as an evil-doer, yet neither his judge nor his prosecutors could find that he had done any evil.\" Matthew 27:",
    "Commentary Vol. 91": "Henry: \"The Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` suffered as an evil-doer, yet neither his judge nor his prosecutors could find that he had done any evil.\" [v_Mat_27_25] Matthew 27:"
